04257nam a22006255i 9780814763094DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t19981998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147630947 a10.18574/nyu/97808147630942doi  a(DE-B1597)548201  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN4888.O25bM56 1998 7aLAN0080002bisacsh04a071/.32211 aMindich, David T.Z., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJust the Facts :bHow "Objectivity" Came to Define American Journalism /cDavid T.Z. Mindich. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Objectivity -- t1 Detachment: The Caning of James Gordon Bennett, the Penny Press, and Objectivity’s Primordial Soup -- t2 Nonpartisanship: Three Shades of Political Journalism -- t3 The Inverted Pyramid: Edwin M. Stanton and Information Control -- t4 Facticity: Science, Culture, Cholera, and the Rise of Journalism’s ‘‘Native Empiricism,’’ 1832–66 -- t5 Balance: A ‘‘Slanderous and Nasty-Minded Mulatress,’’ Ida B. Wells, Confronts ‘‘Objectivity’’ in the 1890s -- tConclusion: Thoughts on a Post-‘‘Objective’’ Profession -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Essay -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf American journalism were a religion, as it has been called, then its supreme deity would be "objectivity." The high priests of the profession worship the concept, while the iconoclasts of advocacy journalism, new journalism, and cyberjournalism consider objectivity a golden calf. Meanwhile, a groundswell of tabloids and talk shows and the increasing infringement of market concerns make a renewed discussion of the validity, possibility, and aim of objectivity a crucial pursuit. Despite its position as the orbital sun of journalistic ethics, objectivity—until now—has had no historian. David T. Z. Mindich reaches back to the nineteenth century to recover the lost history and meaning of this central tenet of American journalism. His book draws on high profile cases, showing the degree to which journalism and its evolving commitment to objectivity altered–and in some cases limited—the public's understanding of events and issues. Mindich devotes each chapter to a particular component of this ethic–detachment, nonpartisanship, the inverted pyramid style, facticity, and balance. Through this combination of history and cultural criticism, Mindich provides a profound meditation on the structure, promise, and limits of objectivity in the age of cybermedia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aJournalismxObjectivityzUnited States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814763094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814763094/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LB  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LB  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK